<font color="#FF0000">THE BAD MEMORIES OF VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 21  3:37:30 US/Eastern 1999
</tt><p>
To whom it may concern:<br><br>
The Vietnam War, truly, affected me. But the brain surgery<br>
for an unannounced AVM (Arteriovenous Malformation) revived<br>
all of the bitter, horrible, and traumatic memories that I<br>
had managed, successfully (or so I thought) from those that<br>
I loved and trusted. The epilepsy that developed didn't aid<br>
my mental outlook, one bit.<br><br>
Unfortunately, the Vietnam undeclared War was the beginning<br>
of the end for me. It began with a 23-day boat ride on 23 May 65, when LBJ and his cronies had the audacity to send us<br>
to what could have been my death, and may have resulted in the deaths of the 5,000+ that were stuck on that boat with me. This much I do know, and that is over 58,000 men's names<br>
are on the too little, too late, completely unnecessary Wall<br>
in DC. In fact, a friend of mine has his name there. The little-known FACT that that war could have been COMPLETELY<br>
avoided is NEVER told to the American people nor is the FACT<br>
that it was begun by &quot;flying fish&quot; in the Gulf of Tonkin on<br>
6 Aug 64! Those dumb words were used by none other than our<br>
esteemed president, LBJ, one of the 4 worst presidents of this century. His campaign LIES that got him elected as our<br>
&quot;peace&quot; president are typical of the demagogue he was but hid from the electorate in order to get himself elected, which he, unfortunately for this country and Vietnam veterans, like myself, was! &quot;Professed patriotism may be made the cover for a multitude of sins.&quot; Those words were uttered in Congress in 1864, a century before LBJ concealed <br>
his patriotism from the then-trusting American people who elected him on his promise of peace---a peace that he never even intended to seek! I'm STILL &quot;Proud to serve&quot;-a saying that kept me going while stuck in the Nam, willing to die for &quot;flying fish.&quot;<br><br>

<p><code>-- dey21@mciworld.com  (Dick Dettrey) </code><p>


